			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think summoning more items is not the answer, but a 1 item universal spell (trageted) would help immensely. You can F1 twice to target your pet, and hit it with the 1 item to scale it properly. The question than arrises why not just have the pet come presummoned with that stats? Seems logical to me (though there is a better scaleable way.), nor would it stop summoning weapons because the game would have no clue if you want magic/fire/ice weapons, so those are still needed. The 500 hit point belt, no brainer, want the hit points give it to the pet, and extra haste always nice. 
<br />

<br />
The main argument against more summoning spells is the sheer number it would eventually lead to. Current you may give it 2 weapons, a muzzle, belt, armour, and focus items. Your looking at 6 casts, 7 counting pet, and trading with the pet about 4 times in all. Adding more to that would basically be paramount to say, let me zone in, and the rest follow in a few minutes. Sorry but there is a point more summoning loses out.
<br />

<br />
So the 1 item (make it a belt, so you can't summon the 500 hit point belt we get. Call it an upgrade) you target cast (mage pet only) Now all you do is make the pet, give it weapons, and cast this new spell to armour it. The reason a spell and not out of the box is because you can make many versions with better/worse stats. Actually make it a click proc from an item drop in many zones. That way your pet power grows as you advance.
<br />

<br />
Tier 3 item: Proc a belt with 1000 hit points 100ac 12% haste 15 to all stats
<br />

<br />
Tier 4 item: Proc a belt with 1500 hit points 500 ac 14% haste 20 to all stats
<br />

<br />
Tier 5 item: Proc a belt with 2500 hit points 1000 ac 17% haste 50 to all stats and 25 to all saves
<br />

<br />
Haste will not stack with muzzle, so you save casting and equiping that.
<br />

<br />
Numbers are variable of course. So you get to a new zone, a mage only drop that you click (works from inventory), self targets your pet (so no twinking etc..), and your pet now has all these new stats. You can add weapons, and anything else you currently summon or have available, but the belt as it takes that slot. Benifits are immediate, it scales as you gain tiers in PoP or in GoD. 
<br />

<br />
It can also be the focus item as well, and like the old BL spell raise your pet's level. The thing is, there are versions that scale as you progress in the game. Self only, but your pet is better and being mage only item you  don't roll against every other class in the game. The pet also becomes more survivable, and helps you and your guild to progress. The current form, ok I am in plane of time, and now I get an item to improve my pet at the end game? WTF why wasn't there improvements along the way to help me and the guild get here by using my pet? Makes no sense. Sure the last focus item will help for the next expansion, but why wait that long to get it? 
<br />

<br />
I hope this is a nice compromise against summoning tons of items for our pet. So what you end up with is this:
<br />

<br />
When you login pre-make weapons for pets, so ready to hand to pet when needed.
<br />

<br />
Zone in to exp/raid adventure etc..
<br />

<br />
1: Make pet
<br />
2: Arm pet
<br />
3: Click Item, it targets pet and adds the belt with the upgrades and maybe jumps it a level or more (DING!)
<br />

<br />
Done:
<br />

<br />
Why this approcah over the traditional focus items, it will reduce the amount of items you need to summon for your pets, unlike the current focus items. As soon as you have them, you can retire many spells, and your zone time to ready to engage a mob time just went significantly down. As soon as a pet is made you can send it into battle, and click buff it as it fights. Add weapons as soon as camp clear is called, if no time to do it previously.
<br />

<br />
Calebe</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
