			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Kapaal to answer this question:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Summonable means you can equip other pets, which might be overpowering, so i can understand that - but I would like the ability to pre-summon them for my own use, rather then waste time/mana in the begining of an adventure.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I suggested making it a proc on an item, so there is no mana cost associated with it at all. So there is no need to presummon them for your own use. Make a pet, click the item and pet is targeted, and the belt goes on it. (Again it is an item not a buff, so it can not be dispelled).
<br />

<br />
So really no need to ever make spares of them, and as for cast time, make it 2-5 seconds. Making it longer serves no purpose at all. Click and good to go.
<br />

<br />
As for burnout, no you would still need to cast that, as it is a buff, and can be dispelled. And it gives flexibility to SoE if they decide to upgrade it again with more haste, or ac, dex agility whatever, they can make the new spell, and the mage with this item will get the benifits from it, the same way any mage would with any level of the focus items or not. It allows scaleability via items and spells.
<br />

<br />
The idea of making it an item that can be given to other pet classes would not allows SoE to tune them to the needs of a mage pet. If they knew a beastlord pet may get one or a necro pet, they may scale them back to not over power them, leaving our pets lacking again. Those classes would have their own forms of focus items (proc clickable), to benifit their pets. You still have the 500 hit point belt muzzle armour to give out to others should you want too. Though I would sggest the beastlord/necro pet focus items summon a belt as well. 
<br />

<br />
This idea is how to scale mage pets as a person progresses in PoP and GoD, without worrying about how it affects other classes, and to limit, actually cut back on the total number of summoned items we need to make. I think it covers all the bases, and allows room for upgrading burnout as well, should they consider doing that. 
<br />

<br />
Calebe</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
